"Mixed Precision Framework Building upon widely adopted techniques in low-precision training (Kalamkar et al.,2019; Narang et al.,2017), we propose a mixed precision framework for FP8 training.In this frame- work, most compute-density operations are conducted in FP8, while a few key operations are strategically maintained in their original data formats to balance training efficiency and numerical stability.The overall framework is illustrated in Figure 6.Firstly, in order to accelerate model training, the majority of core computation kernels, i.e., GEMM operations, are implemented in FP8 precision.These GEMM operations accept FP8 tensors as inputs and produce outputs in BF16 or FP32.As depicted in Figure 6, all three GEMMs associated with the Linear operator, namely Fprop (forward pass), Dgrad (activation backward pass), and Wgrad (weight backward pass), are executed in FP8.This design theoretically doubles the computational speed compared with the original BF16 method.Additionally, the FP8 Wgrad GEMM allows activations to be stored in FP8 for use in the backward pass.",155,1084,271,10,15,"[ 2.31678877e-02 -2.76998486e-02 -5.80576546e-02  2.85154022e-02
